Builds two tables—type and construct—from Pass A output to enable programmatic corpus lookup without enumeration. The type table maps strokes to templated type strings with `%t` slots; the construct table records count-resolved entries with type slot positions and fill order, keyed by base stroke. At runtime, the obligation-stack walker (in `walk` module) replays template filling on demand, making expansion cost proportional to strokes pressed rather than `O(T^s)`.

`build_types(entries)` extracts `@type` entries into `InfType` records: stroke, arity, and template text with `%t` markers only. `build_constructs(entries)` runs Pass A (count expansion) on non-`@type` entries and wraps each resolved output as a `Construct`: base stroke segments, optional fuse shape, template with slots intact, slot indices in template order, and fill order (fuse-target first for `@fuse`, otherwise template order per D12). `build_tables(entries)` calls both; `check_fuse_ambiguity(types, constructs)` verifies no two `(shape, type)` pairs merge to the same stroke under the same base—a collision that enumeration would catch as a duplicate but programmatic lookup would silently mishandle.

Fused constructs split stroke on `/`, pop the last segment as shape, and merge it with type strokes; a clash between different type heads fusing to the same final stroke is a hard error. The `emit` and `walk` modules export the table-driven rendering and obligation-stack replay logic.